eventName: Marvin Macmillian - Travels Essex, Kent & East Sussex
story:
I would like to introduce myself my name is ‘Marvin Macmillan’ I will be undertaking a journey of epic proportions as I set out to travel the whole of my current Toolstation region with the help of my colleagues in my region which covers Essex, Kent and East Sussex - I will be starting my journey in one of our Colchester stores during March and ending my journey at Folkestone Via every store in my region without the use of a motor vehicle and spending no more than one week in each store…. My team will be helping me travel in many different ways walking, cycling, running, horseback riding who knows how else I might travel!
I have 25 shops and over 380 miles to cover (that's if I take the shortest route). No one says I have to take a direct route. So stay tuned to watch my progress - while I aim to raise £1000 for Macmillan


Toolstation are proud to be partnering with Macmillan Cancer Support for the next two years.There are currently 3 million people living with cancer in the UK, with someone receiving a cancer diagnosis every two minutes. We know that one in two people in the UK will experience a cancer diagnosis in their lifetime.For more than 100 years Macmillan has been there for people with cancer when they needed them most. Today is no exception!Cancer is not going anywhere. And neither can Macmillan.Join us in supporting Macmillan, so they can keep providing physical, financial and emotional support to the millions of people that count on them.
title: Marvin Macmillian - Travels Essex, Kent & East Sussex

story:
On the 15th April 2013 my mum passed away with cancer . And despite the jovial ‘giving up alcohol’ facade, losing a parent is the hardest thing a child ever has to go through. I turn 50 on 17th Feb 2021 and I would like to use this occasion to raise money for Macmillan!

My mum meant the world to me , no-one can replace her, if my friends and family would like to help raise money for an amazing cause for MY 50TH BIRTHDAY. I would be really grateful!

story:
To help and support the Macmillan charity and all the work they do for cancer research I will be taking part in the David Goggins 4x4x48 Challenge. I hope to raise as much money as possible for a fantastic cause!

The challenge involves running 4 miles, every 4 hours for 48 hours. It will be tough!

I am not an experienced runner, I just run occasionally and haven't done anything like this before. If you would like to join in virtually and support that way, that would be awesome. The event takes place from Friday 5th March (PST). There is more information about the event on the website:

https://www.gogginschallenge.com/

story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising.

For those who don't know in August 2019 my girlfriend was diagnosed with stage 2 Hodgkin's Lymphoma, an uncommon cancer that develops in the lympahtic system.

Luckily, the cancer melted away but needless to say, it was a scary and stressful time of our lives. MacMillan provided much needed information on getting through day to day life both as a cancer patient and as a loved one.

So how do we raise money for them? By having a tournament with the best and most important Street Fighter character EVER, Dan!

eventName: Walking from home, together run by St John Ambulance
story:
Join Taylor Wessing in raising £20,000 for St John Ambulance to support the health of our communities.

We will circle the globe over the next 6 weeks, visiting major cities and remote corners of the world by walking, running and cycling to achieve our target.

As a firm we have almost 70 teams who between 27 January and 31 March will be trying to virtually walk our way around the globe to raise funds for St Johns Ambulance.  They have played a vital role throughout the coronavirus pandemic, none more so than now with their continued support with the delivery of the COVID-19 vaccine.

Their vaccination volunteers are delivering these vital jabs and taking care of people before and after they receive them.

Please help support this amazing service by making a donation, if you can.

Many Thanks

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Mair Hitchings (1935 - 2021)

It is with great sadness that we announce the sudden passing of Mair Hitchings on Sunday 7th February.

Born and raised in Glanamman, Mair trained as a nurse in Morriston hospital, beginning her career as a midwife, before turning to geriatric and palliative care. In 1972, Mair was appointed Matron of the newly opened care home in Tirydail, Ammanford, a position that she proudly held for over 25 years.

Mair’s life was devoted to caring for others. In her retirement from a career in the care sector, Mair started a number of charities and non-profit support groups in the town, including a branch of the British Heart Foundation, The Stroke Support group, and Home Start. She also pursued other interests, including qualifying as a reflexologist.

During their time as town councillors, both Mair and her beloved husband, Godfrey, were bestowed the honour of Mayor of Ammanford. During Mair’s second term in office, she had the privilege of signing the Twinning Charter, on behalf of Ammanford, with Breuillet, France. A devout member, and Deacon, at Christian Temple, Ammanford, Mair was also an active member of the Ammanford Choral Society.

Mair was a devoted mother to John and Liz, and grandmother to Oliver and Lydia. She will be greatly missed by her family and her community. The family wishes to thank those who cared for Mair in her later years, including the staff of Carmarthenshire County Council, the Welsh Ambulance Service, and Brynteg Surgery, for their kindness and support.

Sadly, due to the current COVID-19 restrictions, there will be a short family service at Llanelli Crematorium, at 1.00pm on Friday 5th March.

The family have requested that in lieu of flowers, donations made to The British Heart Foundation, the charity Mair served for so many years would be most fitting and gratefully received.

___________

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
What is the Challenge?

The challenge will involve running 4 miles every 4 hours for 48 hours... that's 2 marathons in 2 days, waking up through the night to get the miles in! We will be starting run number 1 at 8am on Friday 26th February and beginning the last run at 8am on Sunday 28th February. 

Why are we running? 

We are running to raise money for the British Heart Foundation in memory of a few people close to the runners' hearts including Frankie's godfather, Pat Marston, who passed away very suddenly last years, and members of Cameron's family that have passed away or suffered from the life changing effects of a stroke or vascular dementia. 

More recently one of our colleagues, Jen, very sadly lost her Dad to heart failure. Jen has kindly shared why this charity means so much to her family below: 

"As some of you may be aware, my Dad unfortunately passed away from heart failure on the 20th January, after a short period of ill health that began during the Christmas period. The doctors did not , and still do not, know the exact reason his heart began to fail. Over the last couple of months it has been a shock to learn that there is still so much research to be undertaken to learn more about our heart and circulatory diseases. My Dad's story is not unique. Heart and circulatory diseases still kill one in four people in the UK. The British Heart Foundation raises money to research cures and treatments, so that in the future, diagnosis can be made quicker and more of our loved ones lives can be saved."

Raising money for this fantastic charity will help motivate our team when we are running on empty in the middle of the night. Any amount you are able to donate would be hugely appreciated. 

Thank you!

The David Goggins Team! (Henry, Frankie, Alex, Oli, Lara, Cameron and Gary)

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
If you knew Kieran, you know he was always someone up for a fundraising event. If you know me, I also love a challenge and you will know how much I LOVE chocolate and sweets. Definitely a sweet toothed girl over here! So this really will be a challenge. I did this a few years ago with just giving up chocolate but since the pandemic I seem to crave chocolate and sweets more and I thought I'd go the full challenge and also give up fizzy drinks. So please help me steer clear through showing your support for a brilliant charity.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hello and thank you for wanting to sign up for the HATTERS100K Challenge.

The British Heart Foundation turns 60 this year and we wanted to mark the occasion.  With support from Luton Town Football Club the challenge is to walk/run/cycle the equivalent of 60 miles (100K) during the month of March (31 days) which is equates to roughly 2miles/3K per day. This is aimed at getting everyone in Luton
moving following lockdown, improving their health and wellbeing.

If we could get 100 people signed up to each raise just £60, Luton could raise an amazing £6,000 to fund our life saving research and help those 68,000 people in Bedfordshire living with Heart and Circulatory diseases.

Please use the hashtag #HATTERS100K in any social media posts to hopefully create some noise in the Town about our challenge.

Thanks once again for joining our mission to get Luton moving this March.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Every year in the U.K. more than 160,000 people die from heart and circulatory diseases - that’s an average of 450 deaths a day. 

Sadly, my Mum, Dad, Nanna and both Grandads died of heart disease so I’m raising money to help in the fight against this. 

Chocolate has been a staple of my diet, especially  over the last few weeks so giving it up for a month won’t be easy for me but it’s all in a good cause.

So if you can, please support me in my challenge. It might not seem like a big deal, it’s not like climbing Everest, but at the moment it’s going to feel like it to me.

Living in a pandemic has been incredibly difficult for everyone, people are discovering underlying heart conditions, some are becoming incredibly poorly  and some are dying with these unknown conditions. By raising money for the British Heart Foundation,  by completing a challenge for a month, and supporting them to be able to complete their life saving research. 

Undergoing tests related to your heart is incredibly scary  and  the scariest moments of my life...however I am grateful to be fit and well. It will be a challenge to give up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks for a whole month  especially when I have such a sweet tooth. But its nothing compared to the amazing daily research conducted by BHF. 

Please donate anything you are able to! Thanks

story:
Anyone who knows me well enough knows how much I love chocolate so I am taking on this challenge to raise much needed funds for this amazing charity. 

A very special person who I hold dear to my *heart* has riden her horse over the rainbow and is now with my Grandadband her beloved animals. I want to take on this challenge in her memory and help others who need medical support for heart disease and other heart conditions. Please help me, help them 💖 I know times are hard but we all need to come together to do what we can to help those who need us now! 

Thank you from the bottom of my 💜

story: We received a call very late at night that my dad Pete has been taken poorly. My husband rushed to my mums home and I followed on afterwards. I was able to go as my dear friend Lesley came to sit with the children. The paramedics worked very hard on my dad and he was taken to hospital where they did everything they possibly could to save our world. He passed away the early hours of 3/7/2020. This devastated our family and friends. I hope to raise money so that no one else has to suffer what we all went through. We still all miss him so very much.

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
What's happening in the world due to the pandemic is really worrying - you can see below what's happening with the BHF. Some of you may know that around 10 years ago my dad had a stroke on Christmas day, and just over 2 years ago he had a heart attack, leading to him having to have a triple heart bypass. Without research like that done by organisations such as the British Heart Foundation, we wouldn't have as much knowledge on these health issues, or have the solutions we do. So I'm doing this to raise awareness, and hopefully a little bit of money. Please give whatever you can, anything will help! 

...

story:
I am doing this challenge for the British Heart Foundation as I have a very close friend that has had heart problems all her life and currently awaiting heart surgery. My mum also has a stent fitted. Heart problems are definitely in my family as I also lost 2 grandparents to heart attacks. This is such a worthy cause. I am an absolute chocoholic and sweetaholic so giving them up for a month will be hard. I’m looking forward to how giving them up will make me feel. 

The below is information from the British Heart Foundation. It’s so sad how the pandemic has meant they have had to cut their budget research in half.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: I’ve decided this year to take part in the British Heart Foundation Dechox challenge in memory of my Uncle Don who passed away in July 2016. He had heart complications for six months as well as endured surgery before passing away very suddenly and unexpectedly leaving a void that can never be replaced. I am someone who is obsessed with anything sweet, specifically chocolate but I am also working on my own health journey so why not raise money whilst I’m at it? The BHF are known for working tirelessly to combat different heart conditions and sadly they’re facing a huge cut in their budget due to the global pandemic. Despite everything else, heart and circulatory diseases are the world’s biggest killers and therefore, by donating you are helping to save our parents and families from enduring the most wrenching form of pain possible. Even if you can donate the smallest amount, it will be greatly appreciated.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support.

Anyone who knows me knows that I love a good sweetie and I cannot pass by a box of chocolates, cakes, any kind of sweetie without at least having one... but that ONE eventually leads to a WHOLE BOX or a WHOLE BAR! I have decided to give up what I love and have gone Leader of the Snack Pack for the entire month of March!!! That means NO CHOCOLATE - NO SWEETS - NO CAKES - NO FIZZY DRINKS - for 31 days!!!! This is not going to be easy for me!!😫

I have no target, I just want to make as much money as I possibly can for BHF to support this charity - my papa, my only living grandparent a few years back struggled with a leaking aortic valve and underwent a triple heart bypass and new aortic valve ♡ this was a very difficult and worrying time for my family. He fully recovered after a few difficult months and is fighting fit now!! I have chosen BHF due to what he went through with his heart and this cause means a lot to me!

------------------------‐---------------------------------

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Anyone who knows me, knows how much I love chocolate! They also know my youngest daughter, Bridget, has congenital heart defects and has had 4 life saving surgeries in 4 years. 

It is because of charities like the British Heart Foundation that she is still with us today. Without the work of the British Heart Foundation the treatments Bridget has had may not have been known. 

The current covid situation has had a huge impact on charities, reducing their fundraising options. For these reasons, I have decided to take part in dechox. I will be giving up sweets and chocolate for a whole month! This is going to be a real challenge for me, any pennies you can spare will really help to keep me going, and help the British Heart Foundation keep working to save lives of people with the whole range of heart disease. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Ok so those who know me are aware of the regular chocolate and sweets that are consumed so I may have bitten off more than I can chew! 

So here we go it’s all for an amazing cause ...watch this space. 

Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Anyone who knows me will know 2 things about me.... firstly,  I had a little problem with this heart since I was 18. 6 years ago I actually did something about it (I don't like to rush these things). Various forms of monitoring I was diagnosed with tachycardia arrhythmia, an abnormally fast heartbeat. It took over most simple day to day duties and also the sports I love were a challenge! I had to have a surgical ablation which involves having a catheter through the groin and passing electrodes to the heart through the vessel and burning the abnormal heart cells. It was actually totally amazing to witness.. yes I was awake and saw most of it on the screen next to me. They ramped my heart up articfically a few times and then when they could locate the problem, they burnt it .. done. I haven't had one palpitation since and all I'm left with is a pretty cool scar on my chest from the monitor used to diagnose it that my boy believe at the time made me Ironman 😂.

The second thing everyone should know is I LOVE my chocolate and snacks... I wake up thinking of them and I go to bed thinking of them (sadly I'm not even joking). So all this leads me onto this challenge and the reason why I'm going to go 1 month with no chocolate, sweets or fizzy drinks. 

I'm fully aware I have been very lucky even my diagnoses, there are many many more people who have far more serious problems of all ages, and I've also lost a few friends too young to undiagnosed heart conditions. I am also in total awe of heart surgeons and staff who keep people alive all day every day and I always help The British Heart Foundation in anyway I can so this is why I'm prepared to give up my beloved munchies to raise awareness and a small amount to say thank you!!

If you'd like to see me in a mood all March just for the fun of it, as believe me it may be worth a watch 😫, please give a little bit to this amazing charity so they can continue to fight the fight.


THANK YOU ❤


The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation in memory of my Nana Doris who sadly we lost last year to heart disease. I'd be so grateful for your support. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

Everybody's willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need them most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - they can't drop the ball now.

Come on everyone, we can do it together!!!!!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hi everyone, I’ve been a little quiet on here but it’s time for a new challenge and it’s a BIG ONE!! 

To everyone who has so kindly followed and donated many times before, you know the story ..... to newcomers, firstly I thank you for taking the time to read this and now the important part, 

It seems so crazy that just over 15yrs have passed since I last got to spend time with my little Sis. After a nice evening spent with the family, my Sister Jo and her 9 month baby, Katie, went home, prepping things for the next day before going to bed as normal. Unfortunately Jo never woke from her sleep as she passed with what is referred to as SADS, Sudden Adult Death Syndrome, with no known problems at the age of 21. 

Over the last 5yrs I’ve completed half marathons, 10k trail run, 100 mile bike ride, Snowdon Triple Challenge and even a silly (but serious) fitness video on YouTube, all whilst not always being in the best of shape!  

So the new challenge 🥁 🥁🥁 

4X4X48 CHALLENGE

The 4x4x48 challenge includes running four miles at the top of every four hours, for 48 hours. This will result in running 48 total miles (ultramarathon) over the course of 48 hours. The 4x4x48 was inspired by retired Navy Seal and ultrarunner David Goggins. In the past, Goggins has described how he uses this workout to train for ultramarathons. 

Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!
title: Marc's 4 x 4 x 48 challenge

Name: Marc's 4 x 4 x 48 challenge

You will automatically receive a receipt and you can write a personal message on our page.

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

story:
We will be walking/cycling a marathon and some of the guides will be doing a bake sale (all within covid regulations). Please support us.


As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK. It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. story:
1st Hatton Brownies are meeting every week on Zoom and working hard to gain our Charities Interest Badges.  The girls have dicided that we are going to raise money for Guide Dogs to support their work with training dogs to support and provide companionship for visually impaired adults and children.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Hi everyone! I’m hoping to raise some money for a cause close to my heart! Many of you know that my nephew is currently under Great Ormond Street Hospital who are monitoring a condition he has with his brain. He’s my little birthday buddy and I’m so proud of him! I’m going to walk 62 miles, maybe more, in March to raise money for this great hospital! The kiddies no doubt will join in with me and hopefully Oakley will be doing some steps to join too! 


Your contribution will make an impact, whatever the amount. Anything helps. Thank you for your support. I've included information about Great Ormond Street Hospital and Children's Charity below.

Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) is an international centre of excellence in child healthcare. Together with our research partner, the UCL Institute of Child Health (ICH), we form the UK’s only academic biomedical research centre specialising in paediatrics.

Since its formation in 1852, the hospital has been dedicated to children’s healthcare and to finding new and better ways to treat childhood illnesses.

Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity raises money to enable the hospital to provide world class care and to pioneer new treatments and cures for childhood illnesses.

With over 220,000 patient visits every year, we need your support to help us give hope to our young patients and their families.

100% of your donation goes directly to the nonprofit.

eventName: Weʼre raising £85,000 to help fund an innovative piece of medical equipment that will hopefully increase the availability and success of paediatric heart transplants
story:
My family, friends and I set up the Love Hearts Appeal after I received a life-saving heart transplant at the age of 15 at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Sadly, many children who are in desperate need of a new heart never get that chance due to a shortage of small hearts. 

The Love Hearts Appeal has an urgent new challenge. We want to help GOSH and the team at the Royal Papworth Hospital with the introduction into clinical practice of an innovative piece of medical equipment, by financing the conversion of an adult system into a paediatric system, suitable for use in children weighing less than 50kg. This would be a world's first and, if successful, could make a very significant impact on the survival of those children waiting for a heart transplant.

The ability to safely transplant a donor heart from non-heart beating donors could be a big shift to potentially increase the pool of viable donor hearts to help more patients suffering from end-stage heart failure. One of the most important factors in reducing organ rejection is the length of time the donated heart has stored on ice until transplanted; during this time the heart can be damaged and less suitable for transplant.
It has been shown that adult hearts can been kept beating, warm, perfused with blood and for longer periods of time, before being transplanted, using a system that minimizes cold ischemia injury. This system pumps warm oxygenated blood and optimizes the condition of the organ by replenishing oxygen, nutrients, and hormones that would otherwise become depleted. The system can provide continuous monitoring and assessment of the organ until the point of transplantation.

Given the limitations of cold storage, it is estimated that globally 60-65% of donor hearts cannot ultimately be used for transplantation. The use of this piece of equipment could increase heart transplantation by up to 25% in the UK.
To do this we need £85,000 to pay for the conversion of a proven adult system into one suitable for children and to pay for the costs of running a pilot project which we hope and believe will demonstrate the system can be used in clinical practice.
 

Please help us achieve this target as quickly as possible. This system has the potential of saving children's lives. We are hugely grateful for your support. 

Thank you,

Catherine and Family xxx

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
This year I will be running The London Marathon to raise funds for a hospital that is so close to my family's heart for two reasons. GOSH has saved both my sister’s and my own life and have continued to provide countless support for my family for the past couple of decades. 

My youngest sister Millie was diagnosed with severe epilepsy from a very early age and this has meant that she has a very different way of life to most of us! She blows raspberry’s to communicate and is the easiest person to make laugh (which makes me feel like a comedian every day). As much as Millie is a ray of sunshine and lights up every room she’s in, she has needed and still needs 24/7 support and alongside my incredible Mum, GOSH has played a huge role in keeping her alive and healthy, and because of this, she turns 18 this year!

Secondly, when I was 9 years old, I was diagnosed with a life-threatening brain tumor (the size of a golf ball) and had to undergo emergency surgery at GOSH. 

Because it was caught and treated just in time the tumor is now completely gone and I am alive and fully recovered today with no lasting side effects from the operation (or at least none that I know of).  

Funny story: my mum did have a little scare when I started to get my words confused after the operation. I was confusing 'Game Cube' for 'Itchy Cube', and even asked when I would next be taken out in my 'wheelbarrow' instead of 'wheelchair'. 

I can safely say that because of Great Ormond Street Hospital my sister and I are alive and well today. My family and I owe so much to the hospital, so when I got the email saying that I had a chance to run The London Marathon in aid of GOSH I couldn’t think of a better way to help give back to an organization that has helped my family so much. 

Any donations would be hugely appreciated and I will be sure to document this journey.

Thank you all.

Millie and Seb

For more information about the work GOSH does and to find out where Team GOSH's fundraising will go visit the website: https://www.gosh.org/what-we-do

eventName: Isaac & Rory Half Marathon For Cancer Research UK
story:
On Mother’s Day SUNDAY 14th MARCH 2021 my good friend Rory and I will be running a 1/2 Marathon to raise money for Cancer Research UK. We have decided to do this as it’s something very close to our hearts as our families have both been greatly affected by this horrible disease, but also for anyone else out there that has been affected in any way. ❤️🕊

A message from Rory

As my closest would know my family went though a testing two years over 2018 and 2019 when first my Dad was diagnosed with mouth cancer and Mum with breast cancer just 12 months apart. This was a mentally challenging time for all my family as well as physically for both my parents.

A message from Isaac

As some people may know in 2019 my Mum was diagnosed with a rare form of breast cancer & tumour that resulted in radiotherapy surgery and countless hospital visits. This was an incredibly tough and stressful time for my Mum and I and not something I would ever want anyone to go through. 

We both count our blessings every day that our parents are still here and feel it is our duty to do everything we can to help in anyway possible in the prevention, cure and aftercare of this cruel disease, and in memory of those who are no longer with us.

This is for any and everyone that has suffered, knows someone that has suffered, lost someone, or those that are sadly no longer with us. With everything going on we thought there was no better time than now to raise awareness and money for charity very close to our hearts.

We would greatly appreciate any kind of donation no matter how small, and for anyone that can help raise awareness for this charity fundraiser by sharing this across social media, and spreading the message to help raise as much as possible. ❤️🕊

Lots of Love,

Isaac & Rory ❤️

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Mum was diagnosed with breast cancer originally in 2018, after an operation, chemo and radio she was given the all clear. Sadly, a few months later the cancer had returned and quickly spread to various places including her lungs and brain. In a very short time Mum went back into hospital in a lot of discomfort which was so hard for her and heartbreaking for us. Unable to be with her we made the decision to care for mum in her final days at home, something that would never have been possible without Marie Curie. Along with the NHS palliative care team, these ladies changed how we felt about home palliative care, their support meant we were able to spend mums precious last days by her side. Mum passed away on the 10th February 2021, just 7 short months after we found out the cancer was back. She will be very missed by her family and friends but would be so happy to know she is still helping and supporting others.

story:

Thankyou for taking the time to read/interact, I am very excited for this challenge and will keep you all updated with my progress.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Welcome to Marie Curie's Great Daffodil Appeal! Thank you so much for choosing to support our vital work. Your help really does mean the world to thousands of people living with a terminal illness during these difficult times.

This charity is very close to our familys' heart, the care given to Matt in his last few days was incredible and the support Matthew, Lesley-Ann and l have been given has been amazing. So in memory of Matt we would love if you could continue to support us and Marie Curie by buying a virtual daffodil. 

Its been a very difficult year for all of us and charities like Marie Curie depend so much on fundraising like the Great Daffodil Appeal collections to enable them to give more terminally ill patients and their family the care and support which is much needed and appreciated, so please support us in any way you can

story:
Hello, my name is Jacob and I am 10 years of age. 

I asked my mum if I could shave my head to support  a cancer charity,  as I really enjoy helping others. 

It makes me smile 😁

Marie Curie are such an amazing charity who once looked after my great grandma 

My mums friend is also suffering with cancer aswel as others we know

My head shave shall take place on the 10th March. I was originally growing my hair for a new style after lockdown. However, I would rather raise funds and help others

Thank you for your support. Love Jacob xxx

eventName: RNLI Cheltenham & Tewkesbury: The Lockdown Quiz
story:
Are you ready to test your knowledge? RNLI Cheltenham & Tewkesbury have a challenge for you...the Lockdown Quiz!

If you're taking part, then please feel free to leave a donation on this page.

You might need to take a peek at the RNLI website for some research to help.

A big thank you for Quizmaster Sue Milliams for pulling this all together.

About the RNLI

The nearest Lifeboat Station to Cheltenham might be over 50 miles away, but you don't have to live by the sea to support the RNLI.

The RNLI has been operating at full capacity since the start of lockdown.

Our service has been rescuing people throughout the Coronavirus pandemic and our heroic crews commitment to saving lives has not stopped.

Unfortunately, our ability to raise funds has been limited.

The coasts of South West England are popular tourist destinations for millions of holidaymakers, and we want to keep those coasts a safe place for everyone to visit.

The average lifeboat station in the South West costs £158,000 a year to run and we are going to have a significant shortfall in income due to the Coronavirus.

We are asking all our friends and communities to donate what they can to keep us running.

When you and your loved visit the coast, we will always be there to keep you safe, on our watch, there will be no preventable deaths on British coasts.

Please help us fulfil that mission by making a donation to our fundraising page, no matter how big or small.

Thank you.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

story:
Hi everyone I’m Shaan Dulay and I am 8 years old. Me and my momager (mom) will be doing the '100 Miles In March'. This is a virtual challenge that will be taking place, which has been organised by WWF. (My baby brother Roshan will also be contributing.)

You can walk, run or cycle! All you have to do is complete the 100 miles! Whether it is indoors, outdoors or both in March (31 days!). The money raised will support the important WWF conservation work.

Please donate to our 'Just Giving Page' for this amazing charity, we are hoping to raise £100 for the 100 Miles! (The page will close on the 11th April 2021).

We will be putting regular updates on how we are doing on our 'Just Giving Page'. We will also be sharing on the social media sites;  @ecoshaan #ecoshaan - so follow us!

Website: https://shaansecoworld.blogspot.com

Twitter: https://mobile.twitter.com/ecoshaan

Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/ecoshaan

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

Thank you so much!

charity.description: A child dies every two minutes from malaria. We are one of the world’s leading non profit organisations specialising in protecting the most vulnerable from the burden of malaria and other communicable diseases. To know more about how we spend your money and where we work, please visit our website.
charity.name: Malaria Consortium
story:
Brothers Matt and James Rainsbury (hello!) are running the Bath Marathon (our first ever marathon!) on August 15th 2021 to raise money for Malaria Consortium. 

Malaria Consortium is a charity which focuses on the prevention and treatment of malaria, a disease which kills around 400,000 people every year. The overwhelming majority of these deaths are in children under five years old. 

We've chosen to run for this charity because GiveWell has ranked Malaria Consortium as one of the top most effective and cost-efficient charities globally, describing the evidence of its impact as 'exceptionally strong'. According to their analysis, it costs just $7 (roughly £5) to protect a person from malaria with chemopreventive treatment, equivalent to a couple of coffees or a fancy pint down the pub. 

It's easy to glance over these things so it's worth repeating: a potentially life-saving treatment costs less than a takeaway pizza! 

GiveWell also estimates that it costs between $3,000 and $5,000 to save a life through Malaria Consortium, which makes this charity one of the most cost-effective ways to save a life. This is the reason for our rather odd-looking target: as of February 15th 2021, $5000 = £3,596. 

To understand why these figures are so different ($7 and $3-5000), we'd recommend checking out GiveWell's explanation here: https://www.givewell.org/charities/top-charities/citations#Cost_to_save_a_life. While you're there, make sure to check out the rest of the site to see the amazing work which GiveWell is doing. 

With this run, we're also hoping to raise awareness of Effective Altruism. Our knowledge of Malaria Consortium, GiveWell, and other outstanding opportunities to do good, only emerged thanks to our discovery of Effective Altruism, a movement which uses evidence-based reasoning to find answers to the question: 'how can we use our resources to help others the most?'. 

To get the lowdown on Effective Altruism, we fully recommend the book 'Doing Good Better' by William MacAskill. It's a brilliant resource which can help you to learn how to do a frankly incredible amount of good no matter what your life circumstances are. It's the old cliché that 'everybody can make a difference', yet not only is this true, but the evidence shows that the difference you make can be truly life-altering if you know where to look. 

At a time when we're all stuck inside and feeling quite cut off from the world, making a donation to a charity like Malaria Consortium can help us to rediscover a vital sense of meaning and connectedness. Even from the confines of our own homes, it's possible for us to have a substantial positive impact on the lives of other people, and we think that's pretty awesome. 

So thank you for your donations, all are very welcome, large or small! You really will be making a difference; as mentioned above, just £5 can protect a child from this potentially fatal disease. But if we can reach our target, we'll know for sure that, thanks to your kindness and generosity, together we'll have saved a human life.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
We're walking 20,000km from St Albans (UK) to Cox's Bazar (Bangladesh), visiting Oxfam projects along the way. 

We'll see the challenges communities face from conflict, to Covid-19 to the impact of the climate emergency and how Oxfam is responding to support communities to thrive, not just survive. 

With your support, Oxfam can continue its life-saving work, it can continue to put together packages of food, give farming support, set up foodbanks, support education for women and girls, and provide cash to buy essentials.

For each £15 we raise, we could help more women to understand their rights, challenge discrimination and to take up leadership roles within their local communities.

For each £35, we could help families access emergency food supplies. 

£45 could provide one of our new handwashing stations to enable frequent handwashing and disease prevention.

With your support, communities can come together to help each other.

charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

eventName: Martha and John's half marathon fundraiser for the Yemen Appeal
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Martha Hembrough (aged 14 ) and her father John are running a half marathon on 14th March 20121.They started running together during lockdown, running from home and around their local area .They decided to try for a half marathon with a view to raising funds for a suitable cause.

Over the last few months Martha has become  particularly concerned about the situation in Yemen and the plight of the children there. She would like to use her run to raise funds for Unicef to continue its work helping the people of Yemen.

More than three years of fighting has pushed Yemen to the brink of collapse. The children there are currently caught up in one of the world’s most complex and destructive humanitarian crises and are paying a heavy price.

Access to food is limited with widespread malnutrition and disease is spreading rapidly.The conflict is putting children in great danger and millions of them are unable to go to school.

Unicef is working to help in all these areas of need. See more at :

https://www.unicef.org.uk/protecting-children-in-yemen

charity.description: Malaria No More UK mobilises governments, influencers, businesses and the public to end deaths from malaria and wipe out the disease for good. Our mission is to catalyse and inspire the global partnerships, leadership and financing to make malaria no more in a generation.
charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
story:
In 2019 it is estimated that 409,000 people around the world died from malaria - a preventable disease - the majority being children under five and pregnant women (source: WHO). 

Across Rentokil Initial, colleagues are taking part in a 9,000km Race to Kigali (the distance between our HQ and Kigali, Rwanda), including teams from America, Australia, Asia, Europe, the Middle East, Caribbean, Africa, HR, IT, Finance, M&A and Legal. 

By combining the efforts of colleagues walking, running or cycling, each team will ‘reach’ the distance to Kigali. This is our global effort to raise funds and show our support for this vital cause. It all starts on Monday 15 February through to the UN’s World Malaria Day on 25 April.

Andy Ransom: "As a proud patron of Malaria No More UK, I am asking my colleagues at Rentokil Initial, as well as friends, family and associates to get involved in the Race to Kigali. In doing so, helping raise incredibly important funding for Malaria No More UK at such a critical time. Rentokil Initial Cares, our charitable fund, will match every £1 raised up to £100,000.” 

Together we can achieve a Zero Malaria world within a generation.Please show your support.

charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
story: In 2019 it is estimated that 409,000 people around the world died from malaria - a preventable disease - the majority being children under five and pregnant women (source: WHO). 2021 is a vital year in the global campaign to make our world one without malaria. This coming June, the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting and the vitally important Kigali Summit on malaria and neglected tropical diseases will take place in Rwanda. The summit marks a historic moment that will unite global leaders and put a spotlight on the importance of renewed action in fighting malaria. We need more action, more innovation, more funding and more political leadership to defeat malaria and move forward stronger in this new global health landscape. Across Rentokil Initial, colleagues are taking part in a 9,000km Race to Kigali (the distance between our HQ and Kigali, Rwanda), including teams from America, Australia, Asia, Europe, the Middle East, Caribbean, Africa, HR, IT, Finance, M&A and Legal. By combining the efforts of colleagues walking, running or cycling, each team will ‘reach’ the distance to Kigali. This is our global effort to raise funds and show our support for this vital cause. It all starts on Monday 15 February through to the UN’s World Malaria Day on 25 April. Andy Ransom: "As a proud patron of Malaria No More UK, I am asking my colleagues at Rentokil Initial, as well as friends, family and associates to get involved in the Race to Kigali. In doing so, helping raise incredibly important funding for Malaria No More UK at such a critical time. Rentokil Initial Cares, our charitable fund, will match every £1 raised up to £100,000.” Together we can achieve a Zero Malaria world within a generation. Please show your support.

story: Kigali in Rwanda is where Malaria No More will be meeting the Commonwealth Heads of Government in June 2021 to try and secure vital funding. Example: Teams of up to 20 people (x5km per day per person) = 100km per day 90 days = 9,000km Each colleague to walk, ride, run, swim, row…. 5km per day (on average over a week): c. 6,500 steps per day. c. 20-30mins on an exercise bike c. 40-60mins walking around customer sites

charity.name: WaterAid
story:
WaterAid is working to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. 

The international not-for-profit organisation works in 28 countries to change the lives of the poorest and most marginalised people. 

Since 1981, WaterAid has reached 26.4 million people with clean water and 26.3 million people with decent toilets.

eventName: Access' Manchester to Madagascar - 5,777 miles for WaterAid!
story:
From Manchester to Madagascar 

From 15th February, well be walking, running, cycling, rowing and swimming to travel the 5,777 miles between Manchester to Madagascar, all in aid of highlighting WaterAid's work in Antenanarivo, Madagascar.

5,777 miles might take us a while to complete, so we are going to compete in two teams and start at each end - one team in Manchester and one team in Madagascar - and the objective is to meet in the middle by Easter, and see who gets there first!

Well be walking, running, cycling, rowing or even swimming (when allowed!) to help contribute individually and virtually to the 5,777 miles we need to complete together. 

The objective is to improve all our wellbeing, get us all out more in the fresh air and away from our computers, and to raise £5,777 for a truly magnificent cause!

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
By donating the money you save to WaterAid, you can help bring a reliable source of clean water to poor communities who are vulnerable to the changing climate.

All you need to do is give something up for Lent, collect the money you save in a Jar of Change, and donate it to WaterAid. 

Think of something you use or buy often – it can be really small – and then collect the money you save by giving it up. A cup of coffee or a chocolate bar a day quickly adds up, and will help someone like Mouri get clean water.

Or start a new habit that helps the environment and contribute to your jar each time you succeed. Start using reusable bags, cycling or walking instead of driving, eating seasonal fruit and vegetables, using reusable water bottles, or avoiding all single-use plastic.

Across the world, extreme weather makes accessing clean water even more difficult for the poorest people. Rain is becoming more unpredictable. Intense droughts are drying up wells and springs. Floods are polluting water sources with salt and faeces.

In Bangladesh, where nearly 5 million people don't have clean water, those who are least able to protect themselves must watch as their crops fail, and their families get sick as water-related diseases break out. They face yet more uncertainty.

This Lent let’s help to bring the gift of clean water - and with it improved health and livelihoods - so that communities are better able to face the obstacles that come their way.

story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
